man ls -p

Description: Append / to directory names when listing.
Example: ls -p → docs/ file.txt
(ananya㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -p
Desktop/  Documents/  Downloads/  hash.txt  hellooo.txt  hi/  Music/  Pictures/  Public/  Templates/  Videos/

man ls -q

Description: Print non-printable characters as ?.
Useful if filenames have weird chars.
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -q
Desktop  Documents  Downloads  hash.txt  hellooo.txt  hi  Music  Pictures  Public  Templates  Videos

man ls -r

Description: Reverse order of sorting.
Example: ls -r → last file first.
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -r
Videos  Templates  Public  Pictures  Music  hi  hellooo.txt  hash.txt  Downloads  Documents  Desktop

man ls -s

Description: Print the allocated size (blocks) of each file.
Example: ls -s file.txt
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -s
total 44
4 Desktop  4 Documents  4 Downloads  4 hash.txt  4 hellooo.txt  4 hi  4 Music  4 Pictures  4 Public  4 Templates  4 Videos
man ls -t

Description: Sort files by modification time (newest first).
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -t
hi  Downloads  hash.txt  hellooo.txt  Desktop  Documents  Music  Pictures  Public  Templates  Videos

man ls -u

Description: Sort files by last access time.
With -l, show the access time instead of modification.
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -u
hi  Music  Pictures  Public  Videos  Documents  Downloads  Desktop  Templates  hash.txt  hellooo.txt

man ls -v

Description: Sort files naturally by version (e.g., file1, file2, file10).
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -v
Desktop  Documents  Downloads  Music  Pictures  Public  Templates  Videos  hash.txt  hellooo.txt  hi

man ls -w

Description: Set the line width for displaying multiple columns.
Example: ls -w 50
ls -w 50
Desktop    hash.txt     Music     Templates
Documents  hellooo.txt  Pictures  Videos
Downloads  hi           Public

man ls -x

Description: List files in columns, sorted horizontally.
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -x   
Desktop  Documents  Downloads  hash.txt  hellooo.txt  hi  Music  Pictures  Public  Templates  Videos

man ls -y

 Not available (skipped, not in GNU ls).

man ls -Z

Description: Display each file’s SELinux security context (if enabled).
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -Z
? Desktop  ? Documents  ? Downloads  ? hash.txt  ? hellooo.txt  ? hi  ? Music  ? Pictures  ? Public  ? Templates  ? Videos



Activity 1:
part 2
whoami

Prints the current logged-in user’s name.
Example: whoami 
urvija

pwd

Prints the present working directory (current folder path).
Example: /home/urvija

cd

Change directory. Without arguments, goes to home directory.
Example: cd : /home/urvija
cd Documents
/home/urvija/Documents

cd /

Changes to the root directory (/).

cd ..

Goes one level up from current directory.
Example: /home/urvija/Downloads => cd .. => /home/urvija

cd <path>

Change to the given path.
Example: cd /etc=> current directory is /etc.

Activity 1:
part B:
tree command
tree -l -L 1

Show directory tree with symbolic links (-l), depth limited to 1 level.
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ tree -l -L 1
.
├── Desktop
├── Documents
├── Downloads
├── hash.txt
├── hellooo.txt
├── hi
├── Music
├── Pictures
├── Public
├── Templates
└── Videos


tree -l -L 2

Same, but show 2 levels deep.
(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ tree -l -L 2
.
├── Desktop
├── Documents
├── Downloads
│   ├── converted_text-1.pdf
│   ├── converted_text.pdf
│   ├── converted_text_protected.pdf
│   └── hash.txt
├── hash.txt
├── hellooo.txt
├── hi
├── Music
├── Pictures
├── Public
├── Templates
└── Videos

10 directories, 6 files


tree -l -L 3

Same, but show 3 levels deep.
                                                                                                                        
┌──(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ tree -l -L 3           
.
├── Desktop
├── Documents
├── Downloads
│   ├── converted_text-1.pdf
│   ├── converted_text.pdf
│   ├── converted_text_protected.pdf
│   └── hash.txt
├── hash.txt
├── hellooo.txt
├── hi
├── Music
├── Pictures
├── Public
├── Templates
└── Videos


tree /var/log/apt -La 1

Show contents of /var/log/apt, including hidden files (-a), limit depth to 1, and follow symlinks (-l).
─(urvija㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ tree /var/log/apt -La 1
/var/log/apt
├── eipp.log.xz
├── history.log
├── history.log.1.gz
├── term.log
└── term.log.1.gz

1 directory, 5 files
